{"metadata":{"objective":"","lastStepAudioPath":"summary","audioPath":"JCS100/3/Refresher"},"steps":[{"headerText":"","leftText":"<p><span class=\"ju-cktitle\" style=\"color:#025B5B;font-family:lato,sans-serif;font-size:20px;font-weight:bold;\">Balancing your ideas and those of others</span><br /><br />Your family tree has many interesting characters!&nbsp; You have been asked to give a speech about them at a family reunion, and you are writing a brief family history to accompany the speech.<br /><br />You have lots of information from research that you have done and from stories that your family members have provided.&nbsp; You also have plenty of your own ideas!<br /><br />Now you want to learn how to put them all together so that your research provides effective support for what you want to say, and your own ideas come across loud and clear.</p><p><br /><span class=\"ju-small-examples\" style=\"color:#552656;font-family:tahoma;font-size:14px;\">Note:&nbsp; All family history sources used here are fictional.</span><br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p><img alt=\"An illustration shows that you want to balance your ideas with the words and ideas of others from your research and the stories your family members have told you.\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" /></p>","settings":{"showHeader":0,"showAudio":1,"audioPath":"1","hideRightPanel":0,"showNext":1,"delayStep":"0","delayRight":"0"}},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":1,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":0,"audioPath":"2"},"leftText":"<p>Your writing consists mostly of your own words and ideas, but you need to support your ideas with the words and ideas of others.<br /><br />You can present information from other sources using <strong>direct quotations</strong>, <strong>paraphrasing</strong>, or <strong>summarizing</strong>.<br /><br />You decide which of those techniques to use based upon what you are trying to tell your readers.<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<table cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" class=\"ju-table\" style=\"width: 100%;\"><thead><tr><th scope=\"col\"><strong>Use. . .</strong></th><th scope=\"col\"><strong>When you. . .</strong></th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Direct quotations</td><td>want your reader to view the exact words from your source.</td></tr><tr><td>Paraphrasing</td><td>want to present the main points and all the details using your own words.&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td>Summarizing</td><td>have lots of information and want to include only the main points.</td></tr></tbody></table>","headerText":"Integrating sources into your writing"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":0,"audioPath":"3"},"leftText":"<p>It is important to balance your own ideas with the ideas and words of others that you will use as support.&nbsp; Here is one way to structure your writing:<br />&nbsp;</p><ol style=\"padding-left:15px;\"><li>Think about your topic and read what others have said about it.<br />&nbsp;</li><li>Begin with a statement that tells what you believe. &nbsp;<br />&nbsp;</li><li>Insert a paraphrase, summary, or direct quotation from a source that confirms, proves, or explains your belief.<br />&nbsp;</li><li>Explain the importance of the source material.<br />&nbsp;</li><li>Explain the connection between your belief and the source material.<br />&nbsp;</li></ol><p><img alt=\"\" src=\"/images/picture_it.png\" style=\"width: 27px; Ants can be controlled by drawing a chalk line!&nbsp;&nbsp;As Edgar Smith (2012)&nbsp;explains in his book,&nbsp;<em>Pesky Pests,</em>&nbsp;&quot;When ants are on the move, they create a pheromone trail for other ants to follow.&nbsp; Drawing the chalk line breaks up the pheromones, dispersing the army of ants from their&nbsp;march&quot;&nbsp;(p. 21).&nbsp; Uncle Hiram watched ants engage in this behavior but never knew what caused it.&nbsp; Uncle Hiram proved for me that there is a high level of accuracy in old family tricks that have been passed down from one generation to the next.&nbsp; Individuals may not always be aware of the &quot;why&quot; things work, but they certainly understand &quot;how&quot; things work!</span></td></tr></tbody></table>"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":0,"fullWhiteboard":0,"audioPath":"4"},"leftText":"<p>Use the words and ideas of others sparingly and only as support for your own ideas.<br /><br />Your writing should synthesize the material you have learned.<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p><span class=\"ju-labels\" style=\"color:#59595B;font-family:tahoma;font-weight:bold;\"><span class=\"ju-greencheckph\" style=\"color: rgb(8, 164, 125);\">v&nbsp;</span></span> <span class=\"ju-labels\" style=\"color:#59595B;font-family:tahoma;font-weight:bold;\">Includes the right amount of information from sources:</span></p><table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" class=\"ju-tableplain\" style=\"width:100%;\"><tbody><tr><td><p><span class=\"ju-double-space\" style=\"color:#552656;font-family:lato,sans-serif;font-size:15px;line-height:180%;\">Grandpa Patrick Walsh spent his days battling the city&rsquo;s blazes in the 1920s.&nbsp; <span class=\"marker\">He was a noted story-teller and shared many stories about fighting fires with fire engines drawn by a team of horses (A. Jones, 2014)</span>.&nbsp; The horses were beloved for their fearlessness and dedication. &nbsp;&nbsp;<span class=\"marker\">&ldquo;A fire horse was a dedicated creature, and it was always a sad event in any company when a veteran steed was forced to retire&rdquo; (West, 2011, p. 131)</span>.&nbsp; Grandpa Walsh worked long hard days with few breaks, but this was typical.&nbsp; <span class=\"marker\">A firefighter in New York City in the 1920s spent nine of 10 days on the job.&nbsp; Day number 10 was for catching up with family, friends, and neighbors (West, 2011)</span>.&nbsp; Interestingly, I was able to learn what inspired Grandpa Walsh to pursue this career.</span></p></td></tr></tbody></table>"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":0,"fullWhiteboard":0,"audioPath":"5"},"leftText":"<p>Simply including multiple quotations from other sources does not show your reader enough original thinking.<br /><br />You as the writer control your message.&nbsp; (West, 2011, p. 131). &nbsp;&nbsp;A firefighter in New York City in the 1920s spent nine of 10 days on the job.&nbsp; Day number 10 was for catching up with family, friends, and neighbors (West, 2011).&nbsp; &ldquo;Firefighters were often inspired to follow this career based on their own personal experiences&rdquo; (Jones, 2014, p. 37).&nbsp; In the 1920s, fires were both common and devastating in big cities. (West, 2011).</span></span></p></td></tr></tbody></table>"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":1,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":0,"audioPath":"6"},"leftText":"<p>Your reader needs to know when your ideas begin and end and what words and ideas are borrowed from others.&nbsp;<br /><br />One way you can do this is by using a signal phrase&nbsp;such as <em>According to Smith</em> or <em>As Edgar Smith explains</em> and include the source&#39;s date in parentheses.<br /><br />Using a signal phrase is considered citing.&nbsp; It lets the reader know the author of your source.<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p><span class=\"ju-labels\" style=\"color:#59595B;font-family:tahoma;font-weight:bold;\">Using a signal phrase:</span><br /><br /><img alt=\"For example, you start a paragraph with your own ideas.  At the end of your own ideas, you start the next sentence with the signal phrase As Edgar Smith (2012) explains, and follow this with words and ideas of Edgar Smith that support your points.\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" /></p>","headerText":"Using signal phrases"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":0,"audioPath":"7"},"leftText":"<p>Your family history has a paragraph about your Uncle Hiram and an ant invasion at your lake house.<br /><br />The signal phrase near the end of your paragraph lets your reader know that the material that comes before it is your own.<br /><br />It also shows that the direct quotation at the end of the paragraph is borrowed from Edgar Smith to support your own ideas.&nbsp;&nbsp;<span class=\"screen-reader-only\" style=\"background-color:#FA839F;\"> The signal phrase is: As Edgar Smith (2012) explains in his book, Pesky Pests.</span><br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p><span class=\"ju-labels\" style=\"color:#59595B;font-family:tahoma;font-weight:bold;\">Signal phrase in your family history:</span></p><table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" class=\"ju-tableplain\" style=\"width:100%;\"><tbody><tr><td><span class=\"ju-double-space\" style=\"color:#552656;font-family:lato,sans-serif;font-size:15px;line-height:180%;\">Many of you remember when I asked Uncle Hiram for help to control an invasion of ants at our lake house.&nbsp; Hiram told me to purchase a package of thick sidewalk chalk and meet him at the lake.&nbsp; When we got there, he took the chalk and drew several heavy lines across the bottom of the driveway.&nbsp; As I watched, I saw ants divert their path and head away from the house.&nbsp; They would not cross that chalk line.&nbsp; Uncle Hiram was right!&nbsp; Ants can be controlled by drawing a chalk line!&nbsp; <span class=\"marker\">As Edgar Smith (2012) explains in his book, </span><em><span class=\"marker\">Pesky Pests</span>,</em> &quot;When ants are on the move, they create a pheromone trail for other ants to follow.&nbsp; Drawing the chalk line breaks up the pheromones, dispersing the army of ants from their march&quot; <span class=\"marker\">(p. 21)</span>.</span></td></tr></tbody></table>"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":0,"audioPath":"8"},"leftText":"<p>If you do not choose to use a signal phrase, include a citation at the end of the direct quotation, paraphrase, or summary.<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p><span class=\"ju-labels\" style=\"color:#59595B;font-family:tahoma;font-weight:bold;\">Same paragraph without a signal phrase:</span></p><table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" class=\"ju-tableplain\" style=\"width:100%;\"><tbody><tr><td><span class=\"ju-double-space\" style=\"color:#552656;font-family:lato,sans-serif;font-size:15px;line-height:180%;\">Many of you remember when I asked Uncle Hiram for help to control an invasion of ants at our lake house.&nbsp; Hiram told me to purchase a package of thick sidewalk chalk and meet him at the lake.&nbsp; When we got there, he took the chalk and drew several heavy lines across the bottom of the driveway.&nbsp; As I watched, I saw ants divert their path and head away from the house.&nbsp; They would not cross that chalk line.&nbsp; Uncle Hiram was right!&nbsp; Ants can be controlled by drawing a chalk line!&nbsp; &quot;When ants are on the move, they create a pheromone trail for other ants to follow.&nbsp; Drawing the chalk line breaks up the pheromones, dispersing the army of ants from their march&quot; <span class=\"marker\">(Smith, 2012, p. 21)</span>.</span></td></tr></tbody></table>"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":1,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":0,"audioPath":"9"},"leftText":"<p>Is it better to cite your source using the&nbsp;author&#39;s name in a signal phrase or with an in-text citation?<br /><br />The choice is yours.<br /><br />Good writers vary their style to keep readers&#39; interest.&nbsp; Try reading your work aloud and experimenting with both ways of acknowledging the author or source.<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":null},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":1,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":0,"audioPath":"10"},"leftText":"<p>Your family history includes information about your Uncle Frank Webner, who rode for the Pony Express.<br /><br />This paragraph includes two paraphrases and a direct quotation, all from the same source.<br /><br />If you use many pieces of information from the same source within one paragraph, acknowledge the source each time you include a direct quotation, paraphrase, or summary in the paragraph.<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p><span class=\"ju-labels\" style=\"color:#59595B;font-family:tahoma;font-weight:bold;\">From your family history:</span></p><table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" class=\"ju-tableplain\" style=\"width:100%;\"><tbody><tr><td><span class=\"ju-double-space\" style=\"color:#552656;font-family:lato,sans-serif;font-size:15px;line-height:180%;\">The young men who served the Pony Express never submitted a written application or were interviewed for the job.&nbsp; They simply showed up, shook hands, and were hired on the spot <span class=\"marker\">(Andrews, 2016)</span>.&nbsp; Often, several members of the same family arrived at the station looking for work; generally, all were hired.&nbsp; <span class=\"marker\">(Andrews, 2016)</span>. &nbsp; Uncle Frank rode up to the station and within 10 minutes, he was given his first orders. &quot;During the first year of the Pony Express, riders were brought on at the rate of a hundred hires a week&quot; <span class=\"marker\">(Andrews, 2016, p. 27)</span>.&nbsp;</span></td></tr></tbody></table>","headerText":"Citing the same source more than once in a paragraph"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":0,"audioPath":"11"},"leftText":"<p>You can also use a signal phrase to acknowledge the source each time you use it.&nbsp;<br /><br />In this paragraph, you introduce each paraphrase from Andrews with a signal phrase.<br /><br />If you use a signal phrase more than once, then you only need to include the date in parentheses the first time you mention the source.<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p><span class=\"ju-labels\" style=\"color:#59595B;font-family:tahoma;font-weight:bold;\">From your family history:</span></p><table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" class=\"ju-tableplain\" style=\"width:100%;\"><tbody><tr><td><span class=\"ju-double-space\" style=\"color:#552656;font-family:lato,sans-serif;font-size:15px;line-height:180%;\"><span class=\"marker\">Andrews (2016)</span> states that the riders who served as part of the Pony Express were paid very little for their services.&nbsp; <span class=\"marker\">Andrews</span> also mentions that a typical rider rode approximately 75 miles a day before stopping to rest for the night.&nbsp;</span></td></tr></tbody></table>","headerText":""},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":0,"audioPath":"12"},"leftText":"<p>Your family history has a paragraph of information about your Uncle Frank&#39;s daily life.&nbsp; It includes two direct quotations and a paraphrase, all from the same source.&nbsp; Each one is cited:<br />&nbsp;</p><ul style=\"padding-left:15px;\"><li>The first signal phrase lets your readers know that the first part of the paragraph is your own and introduces a direct quotation.&nbsp;&nbsp;<br />&nbsp;</li><li>The second signal phrase indicates the beginning of another direct quotation.&nbsp;<br />&nbsp;</li><li>The last citation references the paraphrase that comes immediately before it.<br />&nbsp;</li></ul>","rightText":"<p><span class=\"ju-labels\" style=\"color:#59595B;font-family:tahoma;font-weight:bold;\">From your family history:</span></p><table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" class=\"ju-tableplain\" style=\"width:100%;\"><tbody><tr><td><p><span class=\"ju-double-space\" style=\"color:#552656;font-family:lato,sans-serif;font-size:15px;line-height:180%;\">Uncle Frank&rsquo;s typical day as a Pony Express rider began before dawn.&nbsp; No matter the station where he had spent the night, an alarm would sound waking all the riders, or cowboys as they sometimes were called.&nbsp; Frank recalled&nbsp;that breakfast was served at long trestle tables and consisted of eggs, bread, and beer!&nbsp; <span class=\"marker\">John Andrews (2016)</span>, author of <em>Cowboys, Cactus, and Craziness</em>, recounts, &rdquo;Beer was served at every meal because of its long shelf life. The cowboys seemed to enjoy washing down the eggs and toast with the dark brew, some downing as many as two or three mugs of beer before setting out&quot; <span class=\"marker\">(p. 33)</span>.&nbsp; Immediately following breakfast, the riders rode off heading in opposite directions: as one traveled east, the other traveled west. &nbsp; <span class=\"marker\">Andrews notes</span>, &ldquo;Riders exchanged advice or warnings about the trail that they had just covered&quot; <span class=\"marker\">(p. 35)</span>.&nbsp; The communication system between riders was of key importance, providing information about weather, terrain, and other threats <span class=\"marker\">(Andrews, 2016).</span></span></p></td></tr></tbody></table>"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":1,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":0,"audioPath":"13"},"leftText":"<p>If you are including information from different authors or sources, then the citation rules apply to each author or source.<br /><br />Your family history includes information on your Aunt Miranda, who spoke against the introduction of non-native plant species in Florida.&nbsp; This is supported by information from three different sources. &nbsp; Each one is cited:<br />&nbsp;</p><ul style=\"padding-left:15px;\"><li>The first citation for the author Petersen acknowledges the paraphrased information at the beginning of the paragraph.<br />&nbsp;</li><li>The following two sentences are your own ideas.<br />&nbsp;</li><li>&nbsp;The next sentence is a direct quotation and citation for the author Ricci.<br />&nbsp;</li><li>It is followed by information of your own about Aunt Miranda.<br />&nbsp;</li><li>You end the paragraph with a signal phrase to introduce a direct quotation from author Ellen Rivas.<br />&nbsp;</li></ul>","rightText":"<p><span class=\"ju-labels\" style=\"color:#59595B;font-family:tahoma;font-weight:bold;\">From your family history:</span></p><table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" class=\"ju-tableplain\" style=\"width:100%;\"><tbody><tr><td><p><span class=\"ju-double-space\" style=\"color:#552656;font-family:lato,sans-serif;font-size:15px;line-height:180%;\">When a non-native plant species is introduced to a welcoming and supportive climate like that of South Florida, the species shows its ability to thrive and spread aggressively outside its native range.&nbsp; A naturally aggressive plant may be especially invasive when it is introduced to a habitat that supports growth <span class=\"marker\">(Petersen, 2015)</span>.&nbsp; Think about a plant that struggles to survive the harsh New England winters.&nbsp; Now imagine that plant transported to Florida and offered abundant sunshine, plentiful rain, and nutrient-rich soil. The plant will &ldquo;explosively take over and dominate the habitat into which it is introduced&ldquo; <span class=\"marker\">(Ricci, 2013, p. 44)</span>.&nbsp; Aunt Miranda knew well the dangers that simple transplanting could bring, and she spread the word, speaking at town meetings, writing letters to the editor, and spearheading a campaign to inform new buyers of the importance of cultivating native species.&nbsp; Local horticulturist <span class=\"marker\">Ellen Rivas (2016)</span> claims, &ldquo;The introduction of non-native species represents the greatest threat faced by the flora and fauna of Florida&quot; <span class=\"marker\">(para.3)</span>.</span></p></td></tr></tbody></table>","headerText":"Citing different sources within the same paragraph"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":1,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":0,"audioPath":"14"},"leftText":"<p>These rules apply to every paragraph you write.&nbsp; Integrating sources into your writing<span class=\"screen-reader-only\" style=\"background-color:#FA839F;\">&nbsp;,</span></th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><ul><li>Use the words and ideas of others to support your own ideas.</li><li>Do not string together a series of direction quotations, paraphrases, and summaries without including your own ideas.</li><li>Try beginning with a statement that tells what you believe, and then insert a direct quotation, paraphrase, or summary of a source that confirms, proves, or explains your belief.</li><li>Explain the connection between your belief and the source material.</li></ul><p><img alt=\"\" src=\"/images/picture_it.png\" style=\"width: 27px; height: 27px;\" /> <a href=\"S3_BUCKET_/JCS100/3/Pictureit_Structuringyourwriting.pdf\" onclick=\"window.open(this.href, '', 'resizable=no,status=no,location=no,toolbar=no,menubar=no,fullscreen=no,scrollbars=yes,dependent=yes,width=826,left=100,height=750,top=50'); return false;\">Structuring your writing: Picture it!</a>&nbsp; <a href=\"S3_BUCKET_/JCS100/3/Screen_reader_picture_it_structuring_your_writing.html\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/images/accessible_icon.png\" style=\"width: 17px; height: 20px;\" /><span class=\"screen-reader-only\" style=\"background-color:#FA839F;\">Screen reader version of Structuring your writing, opens in a new tab</span></a>&nbsp;</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>&nbsp;</p>","rightText":null,"headerText":"Putting it all together"},{"settings":{"showAudio":0,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":1,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":0,"fullWhiteboard":0},"leftText":"<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" class=\"ju-summary\" style=\"width:90%;\"><thead><tr><th scope=\"col\">Remember! Using signal phrases<span class=\"screen-reader-only\" style=\"background-color:#FA839F;\">&nbsp;,</span></th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><ul><li>Use a signal phrase such as <em>According to Jones (2014)</em> to show where your ideas end and the words or ideas of another begin.</li><li>When you use a signal phrase for a direct quotation, include the page number in parentheses at the end of the quotation.</li></ul></td></tr></tbody></table><p>&nbsp;</p><table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" class=\"ju-summary\" style=\"width:90%;\"><thead><tr><th scope=\"col\">Remember! More than one citation in a paragraph<span class=\"screen-reader-only\" style=\"background-color:#FA839F;\">&nbsp;,</span></th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><ul><li>When you paraphrase, summarize, or quote a source more than once within a paragraph, acknowledge the source each time you use it with either a signal phrase or a citation in parentheses.</li><li>When you use multiple signal phrases to acknowledge the same source within a paragraph, only include a citation in parentheses with the first signal phrase.&nbsp;This pattern starts over with each new paragraph.</li><li>When you use multiple sources within a paragraph, the same rules apply.&nbsp; Each time you use a piece of information from a source, you must acknowledge it.</li></ul><img alt=\"\" src=\"/images/picture_it.png\" style=\"width: 27px; height: 27px;\" />&nbsp; <a href=\"S3_BUCKET_/JCS100/3/Pictureit_Morethanonecitation.pdf\" onclick=\"window.open(this.href, '', 'resizable=no,status=no,location=no,toolbar=no,menubar=no,fullscreen=no,scrollbars=yes,dependent=yes,width=900,left=100,height=750,top=50'); return false;\">More than one citation in a piece of writing: Picture it!</a>&nbsp; <a href=\"S3_BUCKET_/JCS100/3/Screen_reader_picture_it_more_than_one_citation.html\" target=\"_blank\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"/images/accessible_icon.png\" style=\"width: 17px; height: 20px;\" /><span class=\"screen-reader-only\" style=\"background-color:#FA839F;\">Screen reader version of More than one citation in a piece of writing, opens in a new tab</span></a><br />&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table>","rightText":null}],"overviewHeader":"Overview"}
